óŸParchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/commands/docs/job_send.mdŸ@46303be6b712239644b1084b340e79c81fc46225e16bad02a910afc4152c5cabØtitle: job sendë®Examples⁄USend a message from the main thread to a newly-spawned job.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> let id = job spawn { job recv | save sent.txt }; 'hi' | job send $id


```
Send a message from a newly-spawned job to the main thread (which always has an ID of 0).
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> job spawn { sleep 1sec; 'hi' | job send 0 }; job recv


```
íêê⁄ÑTitle: title: job send
Path: Examples
Content:
Send a message from the main thread to a newly-spawned job.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> let id = job spawn { job recv | save sent.txt }; 'hi' | job send $id


```
Send a message from a newly-spawned job to the main thread (which always has an ID of 0).
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> job spawn { sleep 1sec; 'hi' | job send 0 }; job recv


```
óŸParchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/commands/docs/job_send.mdŸ@3a1e710aa4a4c221d1bbd00d6cd7776491c52a7bc901c06c82a90f623fcca21eØtitle: job sendë•Notes⁄”This command sends a message to a background job, which can then read sent messages

in a first-in-first-out fashion with 
``job recv``
. When it does so, it may additionally specify a numeric filter tag,

in which case it will only read messages sent with the exact same filter tag.

In particular, the id 0 refers to the main/initial nushell thread.
A message can be any nushell value, and streams are always collected before being sent.
This command never blocks.
íêê⁄ˇTitle: title: job send
Path: Notes
Content:
This command sends a message to a background job, which can then read sent messages

in a first-in-first-out fashion with 
``job recv``
. When it does so, it may additionally specify a numeric filter tag,

in which case it will only read messages sent with the exact same filter tag.

In particular, the id 0 refers to the main/initial nushell thread.
A message can be any nushell value, and streams are always collected before being sent.
This command never blocks.
